        "body1": "Apple has announced the successor to the iPad Air 2. It isn't called the Air 3, but instead just '9.7-inch iPad'. Here's what you need to know about its price, specs and release date in the UK. See also: Best tablet 2017.\n\nThe new iPad 9.7 was announced in a press release alongside a slightly updated iPad mini 4.\n\nClick here to read the latest version of this article.\n\nWhen is the new iPad 9.7 release date?\n\niPad Air 3 release date: 27-31 March\n\nYou can pre-order a 9.7-inch iPad from 24 March. They will go on sale in Apple stores 'next week'. That could mean as soon as 27 March, or as late as 31 March. In any case, there's not long to wait if you're itching to buy one.\n\nHow much will the new iPad cost in the UK?\n\nWe expected the new iPad to cost \u00a3399 for the Wi-Fi-only 32GB base model - Apple's standard price for the full-size iPad. But the tablet actually costs \u00a3339, which is the lowest price for a new 10in iPad.\n\nIf you want more storage, there's a 128GB version which costs \u00a3429.\n\nThe Wi-Fi + Cellular model costs \u00a3469 for the 32GB model. Pricing for the 128GB 4G version is not yet known.\n\nAll models are available in Silver, Gold and Space Grey. There's no Rose Gold option.\n\nSee also: iPad mini 5 release date, price and spec rumours\n\nWhat's new about the iPad 9.7-inch?\n\nWe didn't expect Apple to change the design of the iPad when it launched the iPad Air 2, but the company surprised us by making the already thin and light device even slimmer. It's 6.1mm thick compared with the 7.5mm of the original iPad Air.\n\nThe new iPad 9.7-inch has returned to that 7.5mm thickness, possibly using exactly the same chassis as the original Air (it looks the same in Apple's photos). The main upgrade is the A9 processor with embedded M9 co-processor. This is the chip originally seen first in the iPhone 6S and 6S Plus. We are assuming that Apple has increased its speed for use in the new iPad, but it never releases these figures officially.\n\nThe only other change is that the screen is now brighter. Apple hasn't said how much brighter, and doesn't quote a figure in the Tech Specs section on its website. Resolution remains the same at 2048x1536 pixels, meaning a 264ppi pixel density. The True Tone screen didn't make it to this low-cost iPad and is one reason to pay more for the Pro model.\n\nNaturally, the tablet will come with iOS 10.\n\nPodcast discussion", 
        "body0": "Apple rolled out a new tablet in the wee hours today, dropping the Air designation as well as any numbering scheme and calling it simply iPad. The $329 device will go on sale Friday but in the meantime, the new iPad raises almost as many questions as it answers.\n\nApple\n\nFirst the good stuff\n\nWith last year's A9 processor and a base configuration of 32GB, the new iPad should get the job done for almost everyone. This isn't intended to be a power-uses tablet. For that, we'll apparently have to wait for upgraded iPad Pros at some future date, likely using A10X processors with graphics speed that will exceed iPhone 7. Because iPad now starts at $329 ($429 with 128GB) and has adequate specs for the majority of applications, it makes Apple even more competitive in tablets. The company's market share in the $200+ segment was already dominant and this can only help.\n\nNext, the grim reality\n\nWhat the new iPad won't do, though, is solve two Apple problems with tablet. First, the fact they seem to have upgrade cycles about as long as PCs these days. That's a function both of the lack of compelling new hardware features and the generally outstanding build quality of iPad. But for Apple, that has meant a near-endless string of lower sales quarters for its tablet. Yes, lower prices could help reverse that trend. No, they won't catalyze a tablet boom.\n\nThe reason is that the software issues that keep iPad from replacing PCs for many users aren't going to be resolved soon. From my personal pet peeve -- that cut-and-paste is just awful -- to the lack of some critical apps or functions for others, iPad remains something of a tweener. It is likely tomorrow's personal computer but today's is still a laptop.\n\nThen, the hope\n\nClearly, Apple's decision to price iPad aggressively has especially critical implications for the education sector. Apple has been losing ground to Chromebooks, the stripped down machines powered by Google's software. With a $299 price for education, Apple is taking aim at Google's inroads especially in K-12. Realistically, this move closes the gap but doesn't eliminate it. Chromebooks can be had in bulk for significantly under $200 each and that includes a keyboard. An iPad with one will still run about twice as high. But Apple is showing a new aggressiveness here. It's worth watching how seriously the company goes after schools, which once built the Mac business.\n\nWhy everyone didn't get the far-more attractive $299 price has to do with Apple's penchant for trading incremental margin for what is likely disproportionate lower volumes. But that's a different topic for another day.\n\nMissing in action\n\nApple has finally retired the less-expensive iPad Mini 2, which actually had been the entry-level product at $269. Of course, it's a much older, and smaller, device with just 7.9-inches of screen vs. 9.7 for the \"full-size\" iPad. That made it less attractive for schools and less attractive as a small device period. For most looking at just an e-reader / small video device, Amazon offers increasingly nice tablets for far less than Apple -- starting well below $100. Apple still has the Mini 4, but it seems headed for the dustbin of history soon enough. Priced at $399 and up, it's mysteriously far more expensive than the new iPad despite sporting inferior specs.\n\nIt does outpoint the new iPad in pixels per inch and possibly in screen quality as the larger brother conspicuously is missing both the fully laminated display and anti-reflective coating of other iPads. Still the new 9.7-inch model does have a better processor than Mini 4, which is likely going to be the worst seller of the line even compared to the $799-and-up 12.9-inch iPad Pro.\n\nSpeaking of which, Apple clearly has future iPad plans for upgrades to both Pro models but they weren't ready to roll them out today. Many rumors have suggested the smaller 9.7-inch Pro was headed for a 10.5-inch, nearly bezel-free design possibly without a dedicated home button. Perhaps both Pros are going to that design -- but not yet.\n\nOn the offensive\n\nStill, even with just the one new model and some confusion around the fate of the Mini, Apple has continued its recent spate of aggressive pricing here. (See Apple Watch Series 1 and AirPods for other examples where the Cupertino crowd has turned the Apple tax into a discount. h/t Neil Cybart of Above Avalon.)\n\nThe bet seems now to be on getting more people into the Apple ecosystem at more attractive prices. Indeed, today's announcements also included a bump of the entry level iPhone SE to 32GB minimum while maintaining its $399 price tag. While Chromebook is the main target of the new iPad, Apple is also doubtless aware than Amazon has been eroded its position, especially with children. Frugal parents who are invested in Amazon's ecosystem anyway see the offerings from the e-commerce giant and often find them hard to resist.\n\nBut Apple has been playing the long game with iPad for a while now, with CEO Tim Cook constantly saying he believes in the product even as sales have waned in recent years. The new model might not be a game changer, but it should keep Apple atop the leaderboard for more than enough time to upgrade the Pros, iPad's software, and whatever else the company has on tap.\n\nFollow me on Twitter. Read the rest of my Forbes posts here.", 
